Fall zones.

A fall zone is a rectangular area where the player never takes fall damage — any drop into it lands soft, no matter how far the player fell to get there. It's the entity for cushioned landings: water, a haystack, deep snow, a crash mat, a safety net, the bottom of a chute. Anywhere the player is meant to plummet without getting hurt, a fall zone is what makes the landing safe.

How a fall zone works.

Normally, dropping more than a short distance injures the player when they hit the ground — a long fall hurts. A fall zone overrides that for the tiles it covers: any landing inside it is treated as a soft landing, so the player can fall from any height into the zone and touch down unharmed. What matters is where the player lands, not where they fell from, so a fall zone placed at the foot of a tall drop turns a deadly plunge into a harmless one.

A fall zone has no sound and no effect other than cancelling fall damage. It doesn't slow the fall or move the player; it simply removes the impact's sting.

Fall zone fields.

The fall zone form takes the following:

Coordinates. A minimum and maximum x and a minimum and maximum y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), marking the rectangular volume that catches falls.

Authoring fall zones by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a fall zone is: fall_zone minx maxx miny maxy. On 3d maps a minimum and maximum z follow the y pair: fall_zone minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz. There are no other fields — the line is nothing but the entity name and its bounds.
